<gtr:projectOverview xmlns:gtr="http://gtr.ukri.org/api"><gtr:projectComposition><gtr:collaborations/><gtr:leadResearchOrganisation url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/C4145C68-58B8-441E-86DD-A4079B65B478"><gtr:id>C4145C68-58B8-441E-86DD-A4079B65B478</gtr:id><gtr:name>MRC Institute of Hearing Research</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>University Park</gtr:line1><gtr:line4>Nottingham</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>NG7 2RD</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>East Midlands</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:typeInd>RO</gtr:typeInd></gtr:leadResearchOrganisation><gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:organisationRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/C4145C68-58B8-441E-86DD-A4079B65B478"><gtr:id>C4145C68-58B8-441E-86DD-A4079B65B478</gtr:id><gtr:name>MRC Institute of Hearing Research</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>University Park</gtr:line1><gtr:line4>Nottingham</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>NG7 2RD</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>East Midlands</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>LEAD_RO</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/39DDCB99-3651-4B2D-9450-175D10C5DEDD"><gtr:id>39DDCB99-3651-4B2D-9450-175D10C5DEDD</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Michael</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Akeroyd</gtr:surname><gtr:orcidId>0000-0002-7182-9209</gtr:orcidId><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=MC_U135079290"><gtr:id>57D1D66C-F789-40D4-8E9E-17DE9781F653</gtr:id><gtr:title>Benefits of, and candidature for, hearing aid processing and fitting features</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Intramural</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>MC_U135079290</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>Modern digital hearing aids offer great opportunities to hearing impaired listeners. But not all features deliver benefit to all listeners: we seek to understand what benefits (or sometimes penalties) are given by hearing aids in realistic listening situations and if it is possible to predict which listener will obtain benefit from which feature.</gtr:abstractText><gtr:technicalSummary>Modern hearing aids, particularly those based upon digital technology, offer opportunities to include advanced signal-processing and fitting features, such as compression systems, noise reduction, directional microphones and speech enhancement. Each signal-processing and fitting feature carries potential benefits, but also potential penalties. We aim to study the ways in which the impairments which accompany sensorineural hearing loss impact upon auditory disabilities and lead to particular requirements for such features in hearing aids. 

Our previous work has studied candidature for non-linear amplitude compression, not only in terms of simple abilities to understand speech, but also in terms of the active listening tasks that people require to undertake in everyday listening. We have also studied some of the psychoacoustic foundations of such listening, such as the the ability of hearing impaired listeners to discriminate differences in some parameters of the compression. 

Our current experiments are measuring the effects of hearing aids on auditory distance perception, as sound level underpins auditory judgements of distance yet both compression and directional microphones would be expected to interfere with level.

Note that this programme has been replaced from 2009/10 onwards by the programme &amp;quot;Auditory disability and spatial hearing&amp;quot;. See www.ihr.mrc.ac.uk/research2009/index.php?page=8 for details.</gtr:technicalSummary><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2009-03-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C"><gtr:id>C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C</gtr:id><gtr:name>MRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2004-04-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>EXPENDITURE_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>236871</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>02CFBECB-FDD1-4EC9-A724-F9EE9E5303F5</gtr:id><gtr:title>Discrimination of release time constants in hearing-aid compressors.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>International journal of audiology</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/1651bca8eeea21bfa1ebb5b8828297c8"><gtr:id>1651bca8eeea21bfa1ebb5b8828297c8</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Gilbert G</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2008-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:issn>1499-2027</gtr:issn><gtr:outcomeId>FDD67982AAB</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication></gtr:publications><gtr:identifiers><gtr:identifier type="RCUK">MC_U135079290</gtr:identifier></gtr:identifiers><gtr:healthCategories><gtr:healthCategory><gtr:id>5585DDA6-FCF6-4B64-8332-1BDFE62CE94E</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>100</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Ear</gtr:text></gtr:healthCategory></gtr:healthCategories><gtr:researchActivities><gtr:researchActivity><gtr:id>93E3E424-8678-4BDD